
[1]fiddle

   FID'DLE, n. [L. fides, fidicula.] A stringed instrument of music; a
   violin.

   FID'DLE, v.i.

   1. To play on a fiddle or violin.

   Themistocles said he could not fiddle, but he could make a small town a
   great city.

   It is said that Nero fiddled, when Rome was in flames.

   2. To trifle; to shift the hands often and do nothing, like a fellow
   that plays on a fiddle.

   Good cooks cannot abide what they call fiddling work.

                  FID'DLE, v.t. To play a tune on a fiddle.
